monster part.” He depicts his music comrades — Tom Verlaine, Robert Quine, Patti

Smith, Lester Bangs — and all the girls he’s loved before. (Hell was the punk

Leonard Cohen in that department.) He quips about his popularity with critics,

“because they were predisposed to favor noise, intellect, and failure.” In the final

scene, he runs into his old nemesis Verlaine for the first time in years — flipping

through the dollar bins outside the Strand Bookstore — and walks away in tears, musing, “We were like two monsters confiding.”